Answer:
Max Planck (Nobel 1918) — originator of the quantum hypothesis (1900): introduced energy quanta E = hν, derived Planck’s law for blackbody radiation and introduced Planck’s constant h (foundation of quantum theory);
Wilhelm Wien (Nobel 1911) — Wien’s displacement law and Wien radiation law/approximation for blackbody spectra (an important empirical/theoretical step that shaped Planck’s work);
John William Strutt, Lord Rayleigh (Nobel 1904) — classical derivations (leading to the Rayleigh–Jeans result) and scattering work whose failure at short wavelengths (the “ultraviolet catastrophe”) underscored the need for quantization;
Hendrik A. Lorentz (Nobel 1902) — classical electron theory and the Lorentz oscillator model and theoretical explanation of the Zeeman effect; his electron/radiation theory provided groundwork later incorporated into quantum models;
Pieter Zeeman (Nobel 1902) — discovered the Zeeman effect (splitting of spectral lines in a magnetic field), crucial experimental evidence about atomic structure and electron behavior that quantum theory had to explain;
Philipp Lenard (Nobel 1905) — systematic experiments on cathode rays and the photoelectric effect (Lenard’s experiments), providing the empirical basis that led to Einstein’s photon explanation;
J. J. Thomson (Nobel 1906) — discovery and measurement of the electron (e/m), identification of a subatomic particle that forced new atomic models subsequently addressed by quantum theory;
Henri Becquerel; Pierre Curie; Marie Curie (Nobel 1903) — discovery and characterization of radioactivity and new radioactive elements; revealed discrete atomic/nuclear processes that became subjects of quantum/nuclear theory;
Heike Kamerlingh Onnes (Nobel 1913) — liquefaction of helium and discovery of superconductivity (1911); superconductivity is a macroscopic quantum phenomenon and his low‑temperature results posed quantum theoretical challenges;
Max von Laue (Nobel 1914) — discovery of X‑ray diffraction by crystals (1912), proving wave character of X‑rays and enabling measurement of atomic spacings (key experimental input for atomic/quantum models);
William H. Bragg & William L. Bragg (Nobel 1915) — formulated Bragg’s law and founded X‑ray crystallography for determining crystal and atomic structures (essential empirical foundation for quantum descriptions of solids and atoms);
Charles G. Barkla (Nobel 1917) — showed X‑ray spectra are characteristic of elements (characteristic X‑rays), evidence for discrete atomic energy levels and electronic structure;
Johannes Stark (Nobel 1919) — discovered the Stark effect (splitting/shifting of spectral lines in electric fields), providing further experimental confirmation and tests of quantized atomic energy levels.
